coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aStandard economic models assume that many small investors own firms. This is so in most large U.S. firms, but wealthy individuals or families generally hold controlling blocks in smaller U.S. firms and in all firms in most other countries. Given this, the lack of theoretical and empirical work on tightly held firms is surprising. What corporate governance problems arise in tightly held firms? How do these differ from corporate governance problems in widely held firms? How do control blocks arise and how are they maintained? How does concentrated ownership affect economic growth? How should we regulate tightly held firms? Drawing together leading scholars from law, economics, and finance, this volume examines the economic and legal issues of concentrated ownership and their impact on a shifting global economy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aBusiness. 0aCorporate governance. 0aIndustrial concentration. 0aStock ownership. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh  acorporate governance, firms, administration, management, organization, control blocks, concentrated ownership, economic growth, law, economics, finance, industry, venture capital, public, private, trading, investment, canada, taxation, opportunism, trust, inherited wealth, cash-flow rights, dual class equity, cross-ownership, stock pyramids, foreign intermediaries, market business groups, freezeouts, racism, oppression, discrimination, power, nonfiction.1 aArye Bebchuk, Lucian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Robert D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDaniels, Ronald J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGompers, Paul A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabula